,Not Recommended,465780,31667276,Posted: 10 May,all,CharlesBarkley_,"The game does give you fair warning that you'll have to procure your own ROM's.It doesn't give you any warning about the obscene amount of troubleshooting that's necessary to get an arcade cabinet running.What I wanted/expected was an empty arcade, which I could fill with arcade machines, select what type of arcade machine it would be (lightgun, standard, fighting game, etc..) and load up a rom onto it, all in VR. From there just pick up the lightgun, calibrate the gun, bind some controls and have a blast playing lightgun games in VR.Unfortunately, simplicity was not the nature of most arcade games. Instead the game has avery long community guideon how to use the Arcade Builder tool. The Arcade Builder is a seperate program from which you configure your arcade.I started by trying to play CarnEvil (which is apparently one of the harder arcade ROMS to get working). The guide tells me I need to load the ROM up in MAME first, configure it and calibrate the lightguns, then take the saved preset and put it into NewRetroArcade:Neon (This step was only required for CarnEvil and Terminator 2). Of course then I need to use the Arcade Builder to set up a CarnEvil cabinet. I load up the CarnEvil Rom, put in the gun calibration co-ordinates, tell it what BIOS to use to run the ROM, Now I'm surely ready to play, right?I decide to playtest the cabinet on it's own. And.. it runs, at least. But now I'm using a mouse to move a lightgun, the MAME emulator running CarnEvil registers the mouse/lightgun as a joystick, doesn't recognize my keyboard at all except for Tab, which opens a configuration menu, which might be helpful if the configuration menu could accept keyboard inputs. All I can do is left-click to move through the configuration menus, and rebind all the controls to left-click. I managed to get some coins into the machine, somehow, but apparently MAME can't accept ""shoot"" and ""start""and""insert coin"" all being bound to left-click.Let's try heading into VR, to see if MAME will see my Vive controllers as lightguns, maybe then we can bind those controls a bit better? Nope. I load up the game in VR, move over to where I'd set the arcade cabinet up, and it doesn't even appear.When you solve one problem, you create two more. Maybe eventually you can iron out all the flaws. But it becomes increasingly not worth it to continue troubleshooting, I gave up.I don't recommend this game, but it isn't the games fault. I blame MAME in particular for my bad experience with the game, but since NRA:Neon relies on MAME, it has to have it's share of the blame. Would definitely recommend if they find a way to streamline the process of setting up arcades somehow.EDIT:There exists a pack of arcade cabinets loaded up and ready to go on reddit."
