,Recommended,465780,29776307,Posted: 7 February,all,Wolfie,"Push it to the limits...Retro Arcade offers a fun 3D environment where you can setup and play your favourite arcades trough a fancy looking arcade cabinets, play an actual SNES on a old CRT TV, gameboy on an actual gameboy, Watch movies on a projector or listen to nice tunes from the internet... the possibilities are quite endless.As of now the whole concept seems quite shallow tho. Running the emulators require a different set of ""LibRetro Cores"" wich means new'er emulators such as Ps1, N64, Ps2... cannot be emulated at all trough the ""game"" world and only older emulations like NES and SNES are supported.Good:Graphics (The game looks rather nice running on a Unreal Engine)Sound Design (Lots of arcade machines playing audio at the same time generates a realistic feel)Customization (Can make your own art for the cabinets)Bad:Lack of emulation support: Due to the fact that you cant use new'er emulators kind of sets the whole game down a notch, not being able to play Ps2 games or the WiiU titles trough Cemu in the arcade is quite a drawback. If the devs could come up a way to support almost any type of emulator in the game it would make the experience much more worth it.No Fullscreen or closeups: Now the game is trying to emulate a realistic feel of an arcade and it achieves it by using filters and effects over the game screen that make the game look like your playing it on a old TV or monitor, wich makes you not want to play the games more than 10 minutes at a time.Arcade Manager is little hard to useIn all and all the retro arcade is a really fun way to experience your favourite games and if eventually we get support for most if not all the emulators out there, it could become one of the best ways to play emulators."
