76561198286021376,Recommended,465780,29725022,Posted: 5 February,all,Sintex,"The Ultimate Graphical User Interface for Emulators that will one day serve as the all time best experience for old timers like myself wanting to get nostalgic and revisit their childhood.Having owned computers/ console for over 30yrs and even using emulators for 20yrs including MAME I can only say that New Retro Arcade is the true icing on the cake that makes MAME what it should be.Having seen the demo of NRA over 1yr ago it was instantly on my top list of things to have once VR hit the mass consumer market. Since the demo a few more normal style games have been added to the arcade room layout, (Basketball and ball throwing games, ten pin bowling and Air Hockey).NRA offers 2 rooms with a few different features filled with old 80's/ 90's memorabilia and of course Arcade Cabinets for you to setup your arcade games on including the cabinet art work provided by the loving spirited community members like myself. If you prefer those older console games then that too is provided by assigning games to cartridges and swapping them over on the console provided in front of a retro CRT TV.NRA is still relatively new though and so is VR (at least decent useable VR) i.e. Oculus/ HTC Vive so the NRA team still have some features to add for the Arcade experience to finally reach its Climax and hit the G-Spot but for the most part it's all there already having added multiple style of cabinets, 4:3 screens, Vertical screens and Light Gun cabinets not to mention attract videos/ music oh and an old ghetto blaster to play music on.Sadly it's missing the little or big old lady sitting behind a counter offering change looking at you in disgust as if you should be in school.NRA is not without it's problems though, but that problem is not entirely the NRA teams fault it's the times we live in and the NRA team tries to achieve a balance of what can be achieved given pc resources available to the mass.One of the main requests the team gets is for a bigger arcade but i doubt that will happen for many years until more powerful computers are available to the masses. There is of course ways around this that the team is already looking into.NRA looks impressive even with lower end computers when using low resolution gfx/ art work and no attract videos but in order to achieve a truly amazing arcade look you need to use all the features available at high details, (High GFX settings, high resolution art work, high res attract video's and this can hit your wallet in the form of a high end gaming pc and we don't even have 4k per eye VR yet and that will really make NRA look out of this world.Oh did I mention it even has VHS tapes and a cinema room, well it does.If you liked the demo and wondering if you should pay out for the full version then the answer is yes.NRA has an amazing community of people willing to offer support for those who get stuck with the setup.For anyone who uses Emulators then NRA is easy to get to grips with and sadly those who are not can give up too easily without asking for assistance or looking in the right locations to make things easier.So my advice would be to persevere and you will not be disappointed with the end result."
