,Recommended,465780,26137237,"Posted: 20 October, 2016",all,Syrsly,"The best arcade simulator with Vive support!New Retro Arcade Neon is fun for me whether I use VR or not, and it was well worth the $18 to enjoy some 80s tunes inside a room scale VR arcade with emulators and arcade style attractions.  The visuals are very realistic and include PBR (physically-based rendering) and working arcade cabinets and even many non-rom minigames, including air hockey, bowling, dart throwing, mini basketball, test your punch boxing, whack-a-t-rex, and skeeball.  All that plus customizable controls, music, and visuals make this a fun toy but not quite a game you'll play for its own merits.  If not for the roms, which were a pain to set up (let alone find), I wouldn't have much reason to play this over all the other carnival style games out right now for Vive.  This game, however, offers some of the most realistic-looking minigames I've seen, meaning that they look like they came from an actual arcade or carnival somewhere.If you have some friends to play with, this game has some nice social features, including voice chat and multiplayer minigames. However, the game does not offer much in terms of character customization, and there's a clear divide between VR players and non-VR players.  Vive users will find that everything in the game supports the Vive wand controllers and roomscale movement.  However, the arcade cabinets suffer from a tiny bit of input lag from the controllers, so you may still want to utilize a gamepad for those.I recommend you try the demo first.  It's a good demo.  Keep in mind that the demo is severely outdated.  The full version has 2 maps to choose from and further refined VR controls.  There's also an arcade manager add-on for the full version that helps you set up the arcade games and posters and things like that.This is a great way to sell the idea of VR to your friends."
