,Recommended,465780,30597520,Posted: 18 March,all,deeplogic,"I'm going to recommend this game, but with a caveat: Be prepared for delayed gratification. The game is a pain to setup and the configuration tool is external and poorly designed. I'm a developer and, even for me, the amount of configuration was a bummer. You also may need to break out a graphics program to get your cabinet art sorted out - there is no online repository of any sort.But, once you're done with configuration, this program really is a gem. It's a nostalgia sandbox. I've loaded this thing down with my favorite music, movies and videos from my childhood and all the games that take me back. What I absolutely love is that the state is saved as you move away from a machine, meaning you can hop from machine to machine without worrying about restarting each time or working with a cumbersome save menu.I've messed around with emulation over the years, but it rarely held my interest for long as I start to get aggravated with moving through cartridge backups just for a moment's worth of pleasure. I didn't want to sit through an entire game - I wanted to go through a roster of games I used to enjoy, getting a jolt of memories and then move along to another. The work in-between is what killed it for me. This game saves me from that.So, as long as you're prepared for the setup, if this sounds interesting to you in any way whatsoever, pick it up. It's worth every penny, even in its current state. If this company were to shut down today, and no more updates were made, I'd still feel like I got my money's worth.UPDATE-------------I noticed other reviewers saying Anarchy Arcade was better, so I went and tried it out. From what I can see, Anarchy Arcade is meant as a 3D Arcade Style launcher, and definitely doesn't provide the nostalgia-fest New Retro Arcade Neon does. Yes, it allows you to launch any application, but that's it - it just launches it. NRA:N displays the game on the arcade screen, and you can zoom into it and choose what style effects to apply. Was the game on a CRT with scanlines? Was it an HD game? NRA:N lets you decide how you want to view it.Anarchy Arcade is definitely not accomplishing what NRA:N does - they're in different categories as far as I'm concerned, and, frankly, Anarchy Arcade looks like garbage. It allows you to customize your environment, but I can't see ever wanting to look at that for any length. The only thing I can say for Anarchy Arcade is that it does auto-populate cabinet art and that is a feature I think NRA:N could desparately use. I'd like to provide NRA:N with one image, say a logo, and have it extrapolate some interesting cabinet art that, while maybe not original, doesn't require any graphics editing.So, I still recommend New Retro Arcade Neon. I do not recommend Anarchy Arcade."
