76561198075345642,Not Recommended,465780,29269916,Posted: 15 January,all,Cylon Surfer,"Recently got back into this title as it now supports Oculus Touch and a form of stick based locomotion. However, locomotion is where this title really falls apart. Let me explain:In order to move you need to be stood on top of circle marker, if you move outside of this marker you will no longer be able to move. I can understand the reason behind this but it basically means that most of your play session is spent fighting against this mechanic, searching for the circle if you physically moved outside of it. This is frustrating and could easily be resolved by having a button bound which moves said circle to the players current position. Sadly this option is not available.Secondly, stick based walking movement - I'm glad it was included but... It's a simple on or off, the position of your analog stick has no bearing on how fast or slow you move. i.e. you push your stick forward and you start to move, slow at first and quite quickly build up to a full on run no matter the position of you stick, hence you have no direct control over how fast you move through this games environment. Not only is this very bad practice in VR and a relic of past game design but it also prevents the end user from being able to slowly walk around their arcade in order to admire the arcade they have built. Essentially if you don't want to run everywhere like your on steroids or in a  90's first person shooter you end up having to use a start stop approach, press forward and then let go before you start moving to fast, press forward, let go and repeat. This makes for a very unpleasant experience and the game becomes a stuttery mess.I think the developers nailed the arcade environment, it is fantastic and looks amazing. However its impossible to fully enjoy the arcade with such poor movement controls. Resolving this issue should be priority for the development team but there seems to be no interest in doing so, I'm quite confident that we'll see more gimicks such as the playable guitar and drum machine rather than them focusing on resolving the underlying 'bad for VR' locomotion design.There are also other little niggles, like no audio being played when trying to watch a movie from one of the VHS tapes, the fact you are unable to sit on any of the chairs in the cinema (or anywhere else there is a chair or sofa) and if you could your view would be obstructed anyway, the position of the TV attached to the game console makes it impossible to sit down and enjoy and the fact that some of the emulation that works in the demo version of NRA does not work in the full paid for version.In honesty I think the devs need to take a long hard look at the foundations of this game and get things working correctly before spending time on more gimmicks which people may use once or twice and then never return to.If these issues were resolved I would recommend this title. In its current state I cannot."
